Given following implementation of equals:

    public class Test implements Comparable<Test> {
	private int x, y;
	
	@Override
	public boolean equals(Object obj) {
		if (obj instanceof Test) {
			Test other = (Test) obj;
			return x == other.x || y == other.y;
		}
		return false;
	}
	
	@Override
	public int hashCode() {
		//implementation?
	}
	@Override
	public int compareTo(Test o) {
		//implementation?
	}
}

What is correct/most performant implementation of hashCode and compareTo?
Please note - equals uses **OR**, not **AND**

Given following implementation of equals:

    public class Test implements Comparable<Test> {
        private int x, y;

        @Override
        public boolean equals(Object obj) {
            if (obj instanceof Test) {
                Test other = (Test) obj;
                return x == other.x || y == other.y;
            }
            return false;
        }
	
        @Override
        public int hashCode() {
            //implementation?
        }

        @Override
        public int compareTo(Test o) {
            //implementation?
        }
    }

What is correct/most performant implementation of hashCode and compareTo?
Please note - equals uses **OR**, not **AND**
